<HEADLINE>
Bank of England pumps 40 billion dollars into money markets
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Bank of England on Wednesday offered a total of 40 billion
dollars (21 billion euros) in short-term loans to banking
institutions hit by the global credit crunch.
</P>
<P>
The British central bank said in a statement that banks had
snapped up 13.44 billion dollars of an available 30-billion-
dollar loan. Borrowers will have to repay the cash on October 7.
</P>
<P>
The BoE also offered a separate loan of 10 billion dollars that
must be repaid on Thursday. A total of 7.47 billion dollars was
taken up, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of England began last month injecting dollar funds into
money markets as part of a coordinated central bank action.
</P>
<P>
Major central banks agreed to inject hundreds of billions of
dollars into money markets that have been hammered by the ongoing
financial crisis.
</P>
